cause of their use of the stick nests of Eared Hutias. Refuge areas that were estimated to have 115 nests (600-800 estimated individuals) in 1990 increased to 330 nests (660— 1320 individuals) by 2009. Some optimistic counts recently recorded 2500 individuals.",Allen (1891) | Borroto (2002) | Borroto & Woods (2012a) | Hernandez & Carnero (1992) | Hernandez & Sanchez (1987) | Kratochvil et al. (1978 | 1980) | Manojina | Gonzalez & Hernandez (1989 | 1994) | Varona (1970 | 1974) | Woods (1982) | Woods & Howland (1979) | Woods et al. (2001),https://zenodo.org/record/6623667/files/figure.png
