d nocturnal.,,"Classified as Least Concern on The IUCN Red List. Steere’s Spiny-rat is widespread and specializes in riverine, seasonally flooded forest that is not under threat from agricultural expansion. It is part of the fauna in a number of protected parks and indigenous areas and is unlikely to be declining. Expansion of illegal gold mining along many major river systems through its distribution, especially in south-eastern Peru, might impact varzea habitat, and focused field studies are needed to assess this possible threat. Additional studies on distribution, habitat, abundance, ecology, and conservation threats to Steere’s Spiny-rat are needed.",Allen (1915a) | Eisenberg & Redford (1999) | Emmons (1982 | 1990 | 1997a) | Gardner & Emmons (1984) | Goldman (1911b | 1912a | 1912b | 1912c¢) | Hershkovitz (1948) | Janos et al. (1995) | Moojen (1948) | Patton (1987) | Patton & Gardner (1972) | Patton & Leite (2015) | Patton & Reig (1989) | Ribeiro (2006) | Thomas (1911a | 1923b | 1924b | 1926b) | Thomas & St. Leger (1926) | Woods & Kilpatrick (2005),
